ACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">New Wizard Line of Spells</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">I honestly think that, for the majority of the game, we can't complain a whole lot. While we are more powerful in some situations, and weaker in others, as a whole we hold our own pretty damn well against the other classes. Until you hit the high HP mobs of Velious, where suddenly our most uber nukes are a drop in the bucket and our mana is not enough to drop very many of them.<br>
<br>
The problem then is to find a way to increase our effectiveness against such high HP opponents, without significantly boosting our powers in other areas. The key, I think, to this was when someone in a previous post (I don't remember who, I'm sorry!) mentioned percentage damage. This, I think is our godsend. Lets take an example.<br>
<br>
Spell: Cryselle's Crystalline Shatter<br>
Level: 60<br>
Resist: Magic (Lure-based)<br>
Mana Cost: 600<br>
Casting Time: 10.0<br>
Damage: 6% of current HP<br>
(Taunt value of a 1000 damage spell, irreguardless of actual damage done)<br>
<br>
Now, lets see how this spell applies in 4 different situations. First of all, soloing. Most high level wizards solo the lowest blues they can find, it's the most time and cost efficient. Now, given the amount of damage that most wizards can do with a bar of mana reliably, the HP that these mobs can have maxes out at about 8k. So lets work with that. Right off the bat, then, the spell will take 600 mana to do 480 damage. In 10 seconds. Talk about a crappy spell.<br>
<br>
Next would be in a high level group situation. Here, thinks will have more HP. From what I've seen, pre-velious, the average opponent will have give or take 15,000 HP. Crunch the numbers, and you come out with 600 mana for 900 damage. Better than before, but still overmatched in ratio by some of the stun spells even.<br>
<br>
Third situation, the Pre-Velious Ubermob. These suckers have 32,000 HP. Meaning, the spell will take 600 mana and return 1920. Now, it has some punch to it, but though the ratio is good, it's still lagging slightly behind the other top level spell.<br>
<br>
Now, we have the Velious 200,000 HP mob. Here's where the spell shines. 600 mana returns a whopping 12,000 damage if it is the lead off. And while the damage goes down from there (seeing as the damage is based off of current HP, not max) the fight is 3/4 over by the time that it is down to matching other spells. It isn't going to do the job on it's own, but your allies will definately be happy to have you in their group once more.<br>
<br>
Lastly, we have PvP. I don't think /ANYONE/ would be stupid enough to use this spell against a player. Even a 4,000 HP warrior... 600 mana for 240 damage, and 10 second casting time? Might as well hang a 'kill me, I'm stupid' sign from your neck.<br>
<br>
So there you have it. A spell that will allow wizards to once again do significant damage to the new velious uber-mobs, yet not increase our abilities in other areas by more than a fraction, if that.<br>
<br>
<br>
